The Culprit Putin
Moscow—Medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden unanimously stated that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Luckily, because Navalny survived, the relations between Russia and Germany will not deteriorate.
In order to demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel declared that Navalny is "a victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond to it.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also supported this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is responsible for the incident, the European Commission will impose a new round of sanctions.
Regardless, poisoning is prohibited under the international regulations of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied involvement in both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov insisted, "There is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, the head of the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed that this was the act of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to tarnish the Russian government's reputation.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly an attempt to shift blame, but he also revealed a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a prominent political opponent just before the upcoming election, and using a toxin developed by the former Soviet Union, is simply indefensible.
Especially considering that the people of neighboring Belarus are protesting against the August election at this moment, this timing is particularly intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny incident was particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that did it, this murder was a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international political arena (the top villain in the Star Wars movies), intervening in the US election, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK out of the EU, and supporting Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB agent, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny escape to Germany, and why was he quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project to Germany is at risk of being canceled.
This murder clearly was a losing move.
In fact, it has further fueled public outrage against the Russian authorities.
Even if it was not Putin who did it, the claim that Western intelligence agencies were responsible is even more excessive.
If such allegations are proven true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have disclosed the fact that the nerve agent Novichok was used.
More possibilities come from a conspiracy plotted by Putin's inner political circle.
It might be that Putin needed Navalny to shut up before the general election, or it might be due to Navalny's anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political henchmen, although loyal, are quite foolish, and they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, with only a few involved knowing the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts had similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Public Inquiry Commission.
The poisoning of Peter Vorobyev, publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on abuses in the Russian judicial system.
Going further back, there is the poisoning of former KGB officer Alexander Litvinenko in 2006. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russian security institutions.
Just like in Navalny's case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan. Although she survived, she was shot dead in the elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death caused enormous damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the result the Kremlin wanted, and satisfying their master Putin is the ultimate goal of the lapdogs.
Loyalty is the only goal within Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning failed, they would not face punishment.
Because they did it for the president's interests.
Those who want evidence of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must clearly state their position, imposing sanctions on Russia even if their own economies are affected.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All responsibilities that have occurred in Russia are attributed to himself.
